Protons of Medium Energy.

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Canadian Journal of Chemistry, Vol.47, p.2921 (1969)

x4freetext: Subentry O0593003 has Been Corrected
According to O.Schwerer`S Remarks.
Last checking has been done.
Target Material was Finely Powdered Uranium Oxide.
Irradiation Time Varied from 5-Min. To 15 Min.
The Total Formation Cross Section For a=136 was
Estimated As a Function of Energy from the Charge
Dispersion Curves.
/by Authors/.The Measured Counting Rates, Either at the
End of the Irradiation or at Time of Separation from
The Parent, were Converted to Disintegration Rates by
Correcting For Counter Efficiencies, Self-Absorption,
Branching Ratio and Chemical Yield.
.The Number of Determination.
.The Uncertainty is Reported by Authors.
Errors For Individual Results were Estimated from the
Uncertainties in Decay Curve Analyses, Counting
Efficiencies, Chemical Yields, Photopeak Area
Estimation /For Gamma-Measurements/ and Self-Absorption
/For Beta Measurements/.  Where More Than One
Determination was Made the Average Value is Given Along
With the Mean Deviation.
According to ENSDF, Intensity of K-X-Rays is Equal
1.24. /Comment by Compiler/
A 3-In.*3-In. NaI(Tl) Crystal.
- By Authors - Gamma Rays and K-X-Rays Emitted by the
Cesium Isotopes were Measured by Scintillation
Spectrometer.  The Decay Curve from X-Ray Data were
Resolved Into Half-Life Components of 32 Hours from
Cs-129, 6.5 Days from Cs-132, 9.7 Days from Cs-131,
12.9 Days from Cs-136-G and a Long-Lived Tail.

x4freetext: According to ENSDF, Isomer Transition Branch is 99.84%.
Positron Emission Rates of Cs-130
Were Determined by Means of Coincidence Measurements of
The  511-KeV Annihilation Radiation.  The Cesium Sample
Was Mounted Between Two Copper Absorbers 1/16-In.
Thick.  The Annihilation Radiation was Detected by Two
1.5-In.*1-In.NaI(Tl) Crystal Placed at 180 Degree to
The Source.  The Contribution to the Coincidence  Rate
From Nuclear Gamma-Radiation was Monitored
Simultaneously Using a Third Detector Placed at 90
Degree to the Main Assembly.

x4freetext: A 3-In.*3-In. NaI(Tl) Crystal.
.Cross Section Obtained by Gamma-Ray Measurements.
.Cross Section Obtained by X-Ray Measurements.
- By Authors - Gamma Rays and K-X-Rays Emitted by the
Cesium Isotopes were Measured by Scintillation
Spectrometer.  The Decay Curve from X-Ray Data were
Resolved Into Half-Life Components of 32 Hours from
Cs-129, 6.5 Days from Cs-132, 9.7 Days from Cs-131,
12.9 Days from Cs-136-G and a Long-Lived Tail.
The Error in the Computer Analysis was Highest For the
Day Component, Undoubtely Caused by the Presence  and
Interference from 6.5- And 12.9-Day Components. Since
The 6.5-Day Cs-132 Emits a 670-KeV Gamma-Ray, this was
Also Measured and the Cross Section Calculated in this
Way Compared with Those Determined from X-Ray Data. The
Agreement was Reasonably Good.

x4freetext: A 3-In.*3-In. NaI(Tl) Crystal.
.End-Window Proportional Counter.
- By Authors - An End-Window Gas-Flow Proportional
Counter was Used to Measure the Counting Rates of
Cs-136-G, Cs-138-G, and in Some Cases, Cs-134-M. The
Decay Curves were Resolved. The Activities Due to
Cs-138-G with Half-Life 32.2 Min and Cs-130 with
Half-Life 30 Min were Initially Analyzed As One
Component. The Contribution Due to Cs-130 was Later
Subtracted When It had Been Obtained by Positron
Measurements.

x4freetext: The Values of the Formation Cross Section of Xe-138
And Cs-138 were Determined from Two Separate
Irradiations. In One Irradiation,For Example,the Target
Was Dissolved As Soon As Possible After the End of
Irradiation and in the Second an Interval of About 1-
Hour was Allowed to Elapse Before Dissolution.
